title: Delhi Red Fort Blast: 9 Dead, 24 Injured in Terror Attack
description: A powerful explosion ripped through a slow-moving car at a traffic signal near the Red Fort metro station in Delhi on Monday evening, killing 9 people and injuring 24 others. The blast, which occurred at 6:52 pm, was so powerful that it shattered the windows of a nearby Sikh place of worship 500 meters away and set nearby cars and motorcycles on fire. The cause of the blast is still unknown, but investigators are focusing on the final movements of the vehicle involved. CCTV footage shows the car driving into a parking lot in the Old Delhi area close to the Red Fort at around 3 pm and remaining there for around three hours. The driver, who appeared to be wearing a mask, remained in the vehicle. Home Minister Amit Shah said that they are investigating all possible angles, adding it was very difficult to say what caused the incident until forensic samples had been analyzed. The country remains on high alert with extra security measures imposed at airports and along the border areas. India's financial capital Mumbai was also put under high alert. The US state department has expressed its condolences to those affected by the blast and has pledged to continue closely monitoring the situation.

title: Delhi Imposes GRAP III as AQI Turns 'Severe': Ban on Constructions, Schools Shift to Hybrid Mode
description: The central government has implemented stricter anti-pollution measures under Stage III of the Graded Response Action Plan (GRAP) in Delhi-NCR after the capital's air quality deteriorated to the 'severe' category. The Commission for Air Quality Management (CAQM) said the decision followed a sharp increase in Delhi's average Air Quality Index (AQI), rising from 362 on Monday to 425 on Tuesday morning. The spike was caused by calm winds, stable atmospheric conditions, and unfavourable weather, which allowed pollutants to remain trapped near the ground. Stage III of GRAP introduces a series of new restrictions on top of those already in place under Stages I and II, aiming to curb pollution sources and reduce the city's toxic smog levels. Key restrictions include a ban on non-essential construction, closure of stone crushers and mining operations, restriction on use of BS-III petrol and BS-IV diesel cars, and schools shifting to hybrid mode for classes up to 5. Experts attribute Delhi's recurring winter air pollution crisis to a combination of meteorological and human factors, including vehicular emissions, paddy-straw burning, industrial pollution, and firecracker use during festivals. Environmental scientists note that these unfavourable conditions often persist through late November, making sustained efforts crucial. They also call for long-term regional cooperation, particularly with neighbouring states such as Haryana, Punjab, and Uttar Pradesh, to address stubble burning, a major seasonal contributor to Delhi's smog. Residents have been urged to avoid outdoor physical activity, use masks when stepping out, and minimise the use of private vehicles. With pollution levels reaching dangerous highs, Delhi continues to grapple with its annual air quality crisis, and experts stress the urgent need for sustainable solutions to ensure cleaner air for the national capital and its residents.

title: Trump Offers Fair Trade Deal, Promises to Reduce India Tariffs Amid Ongoing Trade Talks
description: US President Donald Trump has expressed optimism about trade talks with India, stating that the two countries are close to finalizing a new trade deal. Trump claimed that India has significantly reduced its Russian oil imports, which led to the imposition of 50% tariffs on Indian goods. He added that the tariffs will be reduced once the trade deal is finalized. India's Commerce Minister Piyush Goyal has also confirmed that the bilateral trade agreement talks are progressing well, with the aim of increasing trade from $191 billion to $500 billion by 2030. Trump also praised Prime Minister Narendra Modi, calling him a friend and expressing hope to visit India next year. The US Ambassador to India, Sergio Gore, has been sworn in, and Trump has entrusted him with strengthening the relations between the two countries.

title: PM Modi Embarks on Two-Day Visit to Bhutan, Strengthens Friendship and Partnership
description: Prime Minister Narendra Modi arrived in Thimphu, Bhutan, on a two-day state visit to further strengthen the friendship and partnership between India and Bhutan. This is his fourth visit to Bhutan, and he will participate in the ongoing Global Peace Prayer Festival, where sacred relics of Lord Buddha have been brought from India. Modi will also jointly inaugurate the 1,020 MW Punatsangchhu-II Hydro Power Project with Bhutan's King Jigme Khesar Namgyel Wangchuck. The Prime Minister will provide aid worth 1000 crore to Bhutan and participate in the 70th birthday celebrations of Bhutan's Fourth King, Jigme Singye Wangchuck. Modi's visit aims to deepen the bonds of friendship and strengthen shared progress and prosperity between the two nations.

title: BBC Faces $1 Billion Lawsuit from Trump Over Doctored Documentary
description: US President Donald Trump has threatened to sue the BBC for $1 billion over a doctored documentary that aired in October 2024. The documentary, titled 'Trump: A Second Chance,' showed a manipulated version of Trump's January 6, 2021, speech, making it appear as if he incited violence during the Capitol attack. However, the unedited speech reveals a different message, with Trump urging his supporters to 'peacefully and patriotically make your voices heard.' The controversy led to the resignations of BBC Director-General Tim Davie and News CEO Deborah Turness. Trump's lawyers have given the BBC until November 14, 2025, to comply with their demands, including a full retraction, apology, and compensation, or face a civil lawsuit. The BBC has promised to review the letter and respond in due course.

title: India vs South Africa: Crucial Two-Test Series Begins in Kolkata
description: The highly anticipated two-Test series between India and South Africa is set to begin in Kolkata on November 14. India, currently third on the World Test Championship (WTC) table, will face the reigning WTC winners in a battle for crucial home points. The series marks the first time since 2019 that South Africa play Tests on Indian soil, and the conditions are expected to heavily favour spin. India's pace battery, led by Mohammed Siraj, Jasprit Bumrah, and Akash Deep, remains equally potent. The series is crucial for both teams, with India seeking to seal a third WTC final berth and South Africa aiming to build momentum early in the cycle. The clash between India and South Africa is more than just another Test contest  it's a battle between the past and present WTC finalists, each aiming to solidify their place in the upper half of the table. With every point crucial in the race to the 2027 final at Lord's, both teams have plenty to play for. India's captain Shubman Gill and coach Gautam Gambhir have arrived in Kolkata, and the team is gearing up for the challenge. The series will be played in Kolkata and Guwahati, and the Indian team is expected to face a tough battle against the Proteas. The outcome of the series will have a significant impact on the WTC standings, and both teams will be looking to emerge victorious.

title: Canada Loses Measles-Free Status Amid Ongoing Outbreaks
description: Canada has lost its measles-free status due to ongoing outbreaks, with 5,138 cases reported this year and two deaths. The country's measles elimination status was earned in 1998, but it has been lost after the virus spread continuously for a year. Experts from the Pan American Health Organization made the determination after analyzing data on Canada's outbreaks. Health officials estimate the measles vaccine prevented 6.2 million deaths in the Americas between 2000 and 2023, but vaccination rates have slipped below the 95% coverage rate needed to stop outbreaks. Canadian health officials are working to improve vaccination coverage and prevent further spread of the virus. The loss of measles-free status is a 'deeply disheartening development' and a 'national embarrassment,' according to experts. The US is also at risk, with current outbreaks in Texas, New Mexico, Oklahoma, South Carolina, and Arizona-Utah border towns.

title: US Partially Waives Caesar Act Sanctions on Syria After Historic Meeting
description: In a significant shift in US foreign policy, President Donald Trump hosted Syrian President Ahmad al-Sharaa at the White House, marking the first visit to the White House by a Syrian head of state since Syria gained independence from France in 1946. The meeting focused on Syria's role in defeating Islamic State, reconstruction efforts, and lifting sanctions. Trump praised al-Sharaa as a 'very strong leader' and expressed confidence in his ability to lead Syria. The US partially waived Caesar Act sanctions on Syria for 180 days, excluding certain transactions involving Russia and Iran. The move represents a commitment to continued sanctions relief for Syria, supporting its efforts to rebuild its economy and restore ties with foreign partners. The suspension of sanctions is part of a broader effort to make Syria successful and a key part of the US's Middle East peace plan.

title: Arizona High School Teachers Face Backlash Over Misinterpreted T-Shirts Linked to Charlie Kirk
description: A photo of math teachers at Cienega High School in Arizona wearing shirts with the words 'Problem Solved' and red blotches, taken on Halloween, went viral and sparked a wave of threats and harassment. Some right-wing influencers claimed the shirts mocked the assassination of conservative activist Charlie Kirk, who was fatally shot eight weeks prior. However, the teachers and the school district clarified that the shirts were part of a lighthearted joke about math problems and had no connection to Kirk. Despite the clarification, harassment continued, with teachers receiving threatening messages and calls, and students expressing unease about attending school. The incident highlights the speed with which online outrage can spiral beyond control, targeting individuals who have no connection to a political controversy.

title: Tribes in Jharkhand make paneer with goats blood:Archaeologists unearth 2,000-year-old fridge in Germany | Top 5 interesting news of the day
description: In Jharkhand's tribal market, a unique cheese made from goat's blood is being sold. The cheese-making process is also distinctive. Separately, a 2000-year-old refrigerator has been discovered buried underground. The discovery and the unusual cheese have generated curiosity among locals and experts alike. While the refrigerator's significance is yet to be determined, the cheese has sparked interest in the region's traditional practices. As one local vendor noted, 'This cheese is a part of our heritage and culture.' The unusual finds have added to the region's rich cultural and historical tapestry.

title: Supreme Court to hear petitions against SIR today:Voter lists to be updated under SIR, new voters to be added in 12 states, UTs'
description: The Supreme Court will hear petitions challenging the Election Commission's decision to conduct a Special Intensive Revision (SIR) of voter lists in 12 states and union territories. The SIR process aims to update the voter list, adding new names and correcting errors. Advocate Prashant Bhushan had raised concerns, stating that this issue goes to the roots of democracy. The Election Commission has assured that the final voter list will be published only after objections are considered. The process will conclude on February 7. Over 51 crore voters will be affected, with 5.33 lakh BLOs and 7 lakh BLAs deployed. Voters can appeal if their name is removed from the list and seek assistance through the helpline 1950 or their BLO or District Election Office.

title: Clash during voting in Jehanabad, 4 injured:31.38% voting recorded by 11 am across 122 seats; EVM malfunction delays polling in Jamui by 4 hours
description: Voting for the second and final phase of the Bihar assembly elections is underway across 122 seats in 20 districts. By 11:00 AM on November 11, approximately 31.38% of voters had cast their votes, a 3% increase from the first phase. However, voting was boycotted by nearly 15,000 voters in Bagaha, demanding better infrastructure. In Jehanabad, a clash broke out between two groups, leaving four people injured. EVM malfunctions delayed voting in six booths in Kishanganj and four other districts. Purnia MP Pappu Yadav claimed the EVM issues were being deliberately highlighted to facilitate vote tampering. With 1,302 candidates vying for the voters' mandate, 3.7 crore voters will decide the outcome. Polling will continue until 4-5 PM at sensitive booths and 6 PM at other booths. The results are scheduled to be announced on November 14.

title: Mercury below 10C in 13 cities of Rajasthan  MP:Bhopal experiences Shimla-like cold; Delhi faces cold wave as temperature drops to 9.9C, AQI crosses 400
description: A severe cold wave has gripped several states across the country, with Rajasthan and Madhya Pradesh experiencing temperatures below 10 degrees Celsius. Fatehpur in Rajasthan recorded the lowest temperature of 6.8 degrees Celsius, while Kalyanpur in Shahdol, Madhya Pradesh, was the coldest city with a temperature of 7.2 degrees Celsius. Bhopal is experiencing temperatures as cold as Shimla, with a temperature of 8.8 degrees Celsius on Monday. Delhi is also experiencing a cold wave, with the temperature at Aya Nagar station dropping to 9.9 degrees Celsius for the first time this season. The India Meteorological Department (IMD) has predicted a cold wave in various parts of the city for the next few days. Meanwhile, a yellow alert for cold wave has been issued in 6 districts of Punjab, with the temperature expected to drop by up to 2C for the next 48 hours. 'This temperature is 5.6 degrees below normal,' said a spokesperson for the IMD. 'The weather will remain dry in Chhattisgarh for the next five days, with no significant change in the minimum temperature.'

title: Isha Deol dismisses reports of Dharmendra's death:Says 'His condition is stable and he is recovering'; Hema Malini slams media for spreading false news
description: Veteran actor Dharmendra, 89, is reportedly stable and recovering after being admitted to Breach Candy Hospital on Monday due to breathing difficulties. His daughters have been called to Mumbai from abroad, and several Bollywood celebrities, including Shah Rukh and Salman Khan, have visited the hospital. Esha Deol, Dharmendra's daughter, clarified on Instagram that her father is 'stable and recovering' and requested privacy for the family. However, Defense Minister Rajnath Singh initially expressed condolences on X but later deleted the post. Dharmendra has been admitted to the hospital twice in recent weeks, including on October 31, and underwent cornea transplant surgery earlier this year. Despite health issues, the actor remains active in films and social media, with his upcoming film 'Ikkis' releasing soon. Dharmendra's fans and well-wishers are praying for his speedy recovery.

title: Families of 'Bahubalis' lock horns in 4 key constituencies:2 strongmens wives clash in Nawada; Anand Mohans son stakes his prestige in Nabinagar
description: Voting is underway for 122 seats across 20 districts in the second phase of the Bihar Assembly elections. The phase sees wives and sons of local strongmen contesting in four seats across three districts. In Warisaliganj, Anita Devi, wife of strongman Ashok Mahto, is competing against BJP's Aruna Devi and Congress candidate Mantan Singh. JDU has fielded Vibha Devi, wife of strongman Rajballabh Yadav, from Nawada, who had won the 2020 assembly election on an RJD ticket. In Nabinagar, JDU candidate Chetan Anand, son of former MP Anand Mohan, is competing against RJD's Amod Chandravanshi. "The people of Bihar are eager to see a change in the state's politics," said Chetan Anand. "We will work tirelessly to ensure that the people's voices are heard," he added.

title: Voting begins on 8 assembly seats across 7 states today:Seats includes Anta in Rajasthan, Tarn Taran in Punjab; results on November 14
description: Voting has begun for by-elections on 8 assembly seats across 7 states. The results will be announced on 14 November, along with the Bihar assembly election results. Key contests include Rajasthan's Anta seat, where a triangular fight has emerged between Congress's Pramod Jain Bhaya, BJP's Morpal Suman, and Independent Naresh Meena. In Punjab's Tarn Taran seat, AAP has fielded Harmeet Sandhu, a former Akali Dal leader. Jharkhand's Ghatsila seat has seen BJP fielding Babulal Soren, son of former CM Champai Soren. The Nagrota and Budgam seats in Jammu and Kashmir have seen intense campaigning, with NC's Shamim Begum and Panthers Party's Harsh Dev Singh facing off in Nagrota, and NC's Aga Syed Mahmood and PDP's Aga Syed Muntajir Mehdi contesting in Budgam. Other key contests include Telangana's Jubilee Hills seat, where a triangular fight has emerged between Congress's Naveen Yadav, BJP's L. Deepak Reddy, and BRS's Sunita. The Election Commission has set up 268 polling booths for 2,27,563 voters in Rajasthan's Anta seat.

title: Who's winning Bihar? Bhaskar Reporters Poll:All exit polls failed in 2020, only Bhaskar got it rightfollow the trends today at 6:30 PM
description: Bihar Assembly elections: Dainik Bhaskar's Reporters Poll to reveal NDA, Mahagathbandhan leaders' chances. The poll, to be aired at 6:30 PM on November 11, is based on inputs from 400 reporters, five senior journalists, four political experts, and two psephologists, along with internal party surveys. The Bhaskar Reporters Poll accurately predicted the 2020 Assembly elections outcome, forecasting NDA to win 120-127 seats, which was the final tally of 125 seats. Stay updated with the latest poll results on the Bhaskar English app.

title: Bhaskar Morning Brief:Explosion in car near Red Fort in Delhi, 9 killed, 24 injured; Voting on 122 seats of Bihar Polls Phase 2 today
description: Bihar Polls Phase 2 Underway: 9 Killed in Delhi Car Blast, PM Modi Visits Bhutan, and More The second phase of polling in Bihar's assembly elections is underway, covering 122 seats across 20 districts. Meanwhile, a car blast near the Red Fort in Delhi has left 9 people dead and 24 injured. The cause of the blast is still unclear. Prime Minister Narendra Modi is on a two-day visit to Bhutan, while the India Meteorological Department has issued a cold wave warning for northern, eastern, and central India for the next four days. In other news, Indian markets have rebounded after a three-day continuous fall, and the country's printed circuit board manufacturing sector is expected to reach 1.24 lakh crore by 2030. Gautam Gambhir, India's head coach, has expressed concerns about the team's readiness for the upcoming T20 World Cup. Additionally, veteran Bollywood actor Dharmendra has been hospitalized in Mumbai, and actor Prem Chopra is undergoing treatment at Lilavati Hospital as a precautionary measure.

title: SC takes suo motu cognisance of Rajasthan road accident:Why sleeper AC buses turning dead trap in India? Are they allowed in several countries?
description: The Supreme Court has issued notices to the National Highways Authority of India (NHAI) and the Ministry of Road Transport and Highways in a suo motu case related to a fatal accident in Rajasthan's Phalodi area. The court has asked for replies within two weeks on the cause of the accident and to conduct a survey of the area. This raises concerns about sleeper bus safety, as eight major accidents in the past three years have killed over 100 people, mostly at night. The court's notice highlights the urgent need to investigate highway safety and the risks posed by sleeper buses, especially on long night routes. 'Most deaths occurred because passengers could not escape in time,' said the court. The NHAI and the ministry have been asked to report the number of dhabas on the highway passing through Phalodi. The recent Phalodi accident and the Supreme Court's notice come as Rajasthan Roadways buses saw a 19% drop in accidents and a 33% fall in deaths in 2024-25.

title: Indian markets open with marginal gains on Bihar polls day:Trumps hint at tariff reduction keeps Sensex, Nifty afloat
description: Indian markets opened with marginal gains on Tuesday, 11 November 2025, following US President Donald Trump's hint that tariffs on India could be reduced. The market sentiment was also influenced by the second phase of Bihar polls. The Sensex is trading at 83,250, down 250 points from the previous day, while Nifty has fallen to 25,500. This comes after a mixed Asian market performance and a 4,076 crore sell-off by Foreign Institutional Investors (FIIs) on Monday. The markets had rebounded on Monday, with Sensex closing 319 points higher at 83,535 and Nifty gaining 82 points to close at 25,574.

title: Nvidias top chips are Nuclear Reactors of AI age:Why India might not be in trouble even if Trump bans their exports of AI chips to desi shores
description: US President Donald Trump has vowed to restrict exports of Nvidia's high-end AI chips, citing their dual use in defence and strategically important industries. Trump stated that only US companies will have access to Nvidia's top-end chips, excluding countries like China. In an interview, Ajay Srivastava, former trade official, explained that India's AI programme operates below the level of China's and can still grow effectively using older but powerful chips like Nvidia's H20 and A800. The US restrictions are aimed at China, not India, and India's AI journey will continue within what Washington allows. Nvidia's CEO has acknowledged a significant loss of China's market due to US export bans, but the company's ecosystem remains the leading choice for most countries, including India, Japan, and the EU. The US views Nvidia's AI chips as strategic assets, akin to 'weapons-grade tech', in the new form of digital geopolitics.

title: Missing Dec 31 PAN-Aadhaar linking deadline will have severe consequences:You cannot open bank account, file ITR or buy MFs and stocks  learn more
description: Aadhaar-PAN Linkage Deadline: What You Need to Know The Indian government has set a deadline of December 31, 2025, for individuals who obtained their Permanent Account Number (PAN) before October 1, 2024, on the basis of their Aadhaar Enrolment ID. Failing to link Aadhaar with PAN will render the PAN inoperative, making it impossible to file Income Tax Returns (ITR) or receive tax refunds. According to the Income Tax Act, individuals with an inoperative PAN may face higher TDS and TCS, and may not be able to initiate certain transactions, such as purchasing mutual funds units worth over 50,000 or opening Fixed Deposits. A 1,000 penalty is currently levied for linking Aadhaar with PAN. The deadline for this linkage is December 31, 2025, for the specified group of individuals. However, those who obtained their PAN after June 30, 2023, are exempt from this requirement. The Income Tax Department is responsible for issuing PAN cards in India, and has authorized two agencies for the application and processing of PAN cards. The deadline for Aadhaar-PAN linkage is crucial, and individuals are advised to take necessary action to avoid any penalties or consequences.

title: Dharmendra- The untold stories of Bollywood's He-man:When actor had paid 20 to light boys on Sholay sets as playful tactic for on-screen romance; considered age just a number
description: Veteran Bollywood actor Dharmendra, set to turn 90 on December 8th, has been admitted to Candy Breach hospital due to breathing issues. Known for his versatile performances and charismatic screen presence, Dharmendra has created a rich legacy spanning decades. He began his career in 1960 with the film 'Dil Bhi Tera Hum Bhi Tere' and went on to star in over 300 films, earning the title of 'He-Man of Bollywood' for his rugged physique and daring stunts. Dharmendra has been open about his personal life, including his secret romance with Hema Malini, which he pursued despite being married to Prakash Kaur. When asked about his age, Dharmendra believes it's just a number, and he continues to work in the film industry. 'Our rapport with Dharam ji was so good that even if I approached him for shooting two days in advance, he never said no,' said producer-director K. C. Bokadia. Dharmendra's journey is a testament to his dedication and passion for his craft.

title: Government Job:Recruitment for 600 posts in RITES; Last date 12 November, exam on 23 November
description: RITES Limited has announced the recruitment of 600 Senior Technical Assistants. The application window is open from 15 October to 12 November 2025. The written exam is scheduled for 23 November. Candidates can apply through RITES' official website rites.com. The selected candidates will receive a salary of 29,735 per month. The selection process will be based on an exam, and the exam centers will be located in various cities. Interested candidates can visit the official notification link or online application link for more details.

title: IND-SA Test in Kolkata under tight security after Delhi blast:Teams arrive amid heightened alert; Police Commissioner to review Eden Gardens arrangements
description: Security has been intensified in Kolkata ahead of the first Test between India and South Africa at Eden Gardens on 14 November. The heightened alert comes after a high-intensity blast near Delhi's Red Fort killed nine people and injured 20 others on Monday evening. Both teams have arrived in the city and will remain under enhanced protection throughout their stay. Kolkata Police have drawn up a comprehensive security plan covering the teams' travel routes, practice sessions, and match days. Police Commissioner Manoj Verma is expected to visit the stadium on Tuesday to review the arrangements. The Cricket Association of Bengal (CAB) is working closely with police officials to implement robust safety protocols for players, officials, and spectators. Security at team hotels has been tightened, with restricted access and continuous monitoring. India and South Africa are scheduled to begin training sessions at Eden Gardens from Tuesday morning, with police ensuring strict security in and around the stadium.

title: Jadeja-Curran-Samson trade talks in motion- Official word awaited from BCCI:Three-way IPL swap could take a couple of days to finalise; all players have agreed- Report
description: The Chennai Super Kings (CSK) and Rajasthan Royals (RR) have initiated the formal process for the IPL trade involving Ravindra Jadeja, Sam Curran, and Sanju Samson. According to IPL regulations, the trade will take 48 hours to be finalized once all paperwork reaches the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI). Sources confirm that consent has been obtained from all three players, and the Expression of Interest (EOI) process has begun. "All three have signed on the dotted line, but it will take a couple of days for the trade to be formalised," a franchise official said. The trade would see CSK send Jadeja and Curran to RR in exchange for Sanju Samson, who was retained by RR for 18 crore ahead of IPL 2025. Former CSK stalwart Suresh Raina has urged the franchise not to trade Jadeja, saying he is a "gun player for CSK and has done really well for the team over the years." The trade is awaiting BCCI's formal nod, which could reshape both CSK's balance and RR's leadership core.

title: 'Felt like a frat house': Canada MP says Pierre Poilievre's party not serious; he was yelled at, called 'snake'
description: Nova Scotia MP Chris d'Entremont has defected to the Liberal Party, citing a 'frat house' atmosphere in the Conservative Party under Pierre Poilievre's leadership. D'Entremont claims he was yelled at by Conservative leaders who called him a 'snake' for considering a switch. The Conservative Party denies these allegations, saying the door was open and the conversation was calm. Meanwhile, Conservative MP Matt Jeneroux has resigned from the House of Commons, expressing disappointment with the party's leadership and faith in the dedication of his colleagues to improving Canada. D'Entremont believes 'three or four' other Conservative caucus members are considering crossing the floor due to Poilievre's leadership style.

title: xQc defends Sydney Sweeney over great genes comment, says outrage is pointless
description: Twitch star Flix "xQc" Lengyel has weighed in on the viral controversy surrounding actress Sydney Sweeney's comment about "great genes." xQc criticized the backlash as unnecessary, calling it "bait" and "inherently stupid." He argued that the phrase was being misinterpreted and that people were stretching its meaning beyond its original intent. "Great genes" can mean having nice eyes, not just being white, xQc said. His comments have resonated with some, but others argue that his defense oversimplifies deeper issues of perception and privilege in celebrity media. The debate continues online, with xQc's response fueling more discussion across Twitch and social media.

title: When Americas H-1B tightens, Chinas K-visa rises: Is the future of global talent shifting east?
description: The United States, once a top destination for international students, is facing increased competition from China. After President Donald Trump tightened H-1B visa regulations, China introduced the K-visa, a simplified visa for science and technology professionals. The K-visa aims to attract foreign talent, particularly in cutting-edge technologies like AI and semiconductors, to fill China's 'skill gap.' While the US still retains its allure, China's K-visa signals a shift in the global talent landscape, making it a potential competitor to the American dream. 'The once-unilateral migration of talent toward the West is now becoming a two-way street,' says an expert. China must now convince the world that it can be a hub for innovation, overcoming cultural and bureaucratic barriers.

title: Nithari serial killings case: SC acquits Surendra Koli; orders immediate release
description: The Supreme Court has allowed a curative petition filed by Surendra Koli, challenging his conviction and death sentence in one of the Nithari murder cases. Koli will now walk free, as he has already been acquitted in all other Nithari cases. The Nithari killings came to light in 2006, after the discovery of skeletal remains of eight children behind a businessman's house in Noida's Nithari village. Koli was convicted for the rape and murder of a 15-year-old girl, with his conviction upheld by the Supreme Court in 2011. However, in 2015, the Allahabad high court commuted his death sentence to life imprisonment, citing a delay in deciding his mercy petition. In 2023, the same court acquitted Koli and Pandher in multiple Nithari cases, overturning their death sentences. The acquittals were later upheld by the Supreme Court in July this year. 'The court has allowed the curative petition, and we will now move to release Surendra Koli,' said Koli's lawyer. 'This is a welcome decision, and we are grateful to the court for its order.'

title: Rural revival, urban strain: Indias jobless rate falls to 5.2% but cracks remain beneath the surface
description: India's job market showed tentative signs of revival in the July-September quarter of 2025, with the unemployment rate edging down to 5.2% from 5.4% in the previous quarter. The improvement was driven by seasonal agricultural employment and a rise in rural labour absorption. However, urban unemployment ticked up slightly to 6.9%, reflecting continued pressure on non-agricultural and manufacturing sectors. The female labour force participation rate (LFPR) climbed to 33.7%, up from 33.4% in the previous quarter, but the unemployment rate among urban women rose to 9%. Analysts caution that while the headline decline in unemployment is encouraging, the underlying patterns reveal fragility, with the labour market expansion yet to be driven by sustained, non-agricultural job creation.

title: Which states work the hardest in America?
description: The American dream has long been synonymous with hard work and dedication. According to the World Economic Forum, Americans work an average of 1,805 hours per year, surpassing Germans but trailing Colombians. Despite opportunities for rest, many Americans decline, fearing job insecurity or disrupted workflows. A recent WalletHub report ranked all 50 states based on 10 key indicators of labor intensity, revealing striking disparities. North Dakota, Alaska, and South Dakota topped the list, with North Dakota logging an average of 39.6 hours per week and Alaska working 41.6 hours per week. "In North Dakota, industriousness isn't an economic necessity, it's a way of life," said a WalletHub spokesperson. "The state's ethos of constant motion extends beyond office hours." The report highlights the cultural anxiety driving Americans to labor beyond limits, with many fearing job insecurity or disrupted workflows. "Hard work remains both a necessity and a source of pride," said another spokesperson. "But what drives Americans to labour beyond limits, even when it erodes well-being?"

title: British Muslim Journalist Sami Hamdi set to be released after ICE detention; wife demands justice
description: British Muslim journalist Sami Hamdi, detained by US immigration authorities for over two weeks, is set to be released and allowed to return to the UK. Hamdi, a London-based commentator, was held for overstaying his US visa, but his family and advocacy groups claim the visa was revoked without cause. The US government has agreed to release Hamdi, who will be able to return home soon. "The government has agreed to release Sami," Hamdi's family said. "He will be able to return home soon insha'Allah." Department of Homeland Security Assistant Secretary Tricia McLaughlin characterized Hamdi as an "illegal alien and terrorist sympathizer," but CAIR's California chapter and Hamdi's lawyer welcomed the US decision to release the British national, stating that it establishes that the government does not consider Hamdi a danger to the community or national security.

title: TBSE Tripura Board exams 2026: Date sheet released for class 10, 12; check complete schedule here
description: The Tripura Board of Secondary Education (TBSE) has announced the schedule for the 2026 Class 10 and Class 12 board examinations. The Class 12 exams will begin on February 25 and conclude on March 30, while the Class 10 exams will be held from February 26 to March 24. Over 38,000 students are set to appear for the Class 10 exams and nearly 30,000 for Class 12. TBSE has released a detailed subject-wise timetable to help students prepare in advance. "Students are advised to download the official timetable from the board's website for subject-wise details," said a TBSE spokesperson. "Follow the official timetable, revise previous question papers, and focus on key subjects early to manage time effectively during the board season," added the spokesperson. The practical examinations for both classes will be held from November 17 to December 1, 2025. TBSE has stated that all exams will follow the prescribed curriculum. Students are encouraged to revise and complete laboratory and project work within the given window to ensure they are well-prepared for the theory exams.

title: Sourav Ganguly blasts selectors for Shami snub: 'Don't see any reason'
description: Former India captain Sourav Ganguly has expressed his support for Mohammed Shami's return to the national team in all formats. Ganguly praised Shami's fitness and bowling skills, stating that he is 'bowling exceptionally well' and 'fit.' Despite not being picked for the upcoming two-Test series against South Africa, Ganguly believes Shami's skillset is 'enormous' and he should continue playing for India in Test matches, One-day cricket, and T20 cricket. Ganguly's comments come after Shami took 15 wickets for Bengal in the Ranji Trophy and underwent ankle surgery after the 2023 ODI World Cup. The selectors' decision to overlook Shami may be influenced by his injury history, particularly with the 2027 ODI World Cup still two years away.

title: 'People are pissed': Democrats fume over Senate shutdown deal, blame Chuck Schumer
description: A heated Democratic caucus call on Monday turned into an airing of grievances as lawmakers expressed frustration over a bipartisan deal with Republicans to reopen the government. Over a dozen Democrats spoke, with nearly all criticizing the compromise. House Minority Leader Hakeem Jeffries instructed members to focus criticism on Republicans, not fellow Democrats. The deal, which requires 60 votes to pass, has sparked anger among progressive and moderate House Democrats, with some calling for Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer to step aside. "People are f**king pissed," said Rep Melanie Stansbury (D-N.M.). "He's the leader of the Senate. This deal would never have happened if he had not blessed it," said Rep Ro Khanna. Despite the backlash, some centrist members have expressed openness to the Senate deal.

title: Microsoft AI CEO warns: Calls Metas AI risky; says not going to be good
description: Microsoft's AI chief Mustafa Suleyman is cautioning against the unchecked development of superintelligent systems, advocating for a 'humanist' approach that prioritizes human control. Suleyman, who unveiled Microsoft's new MAI Superintelligence Team, emphasizes that AI should be built for humanity's sake, not just for its own sake. He rejects the idea of an 'AI race to AGI' and instead focuses on practical applications like medical AI, personalized education companions, and clean energy innovations. Suleyman acknowledges the risks of his approach, including potential cost and inefficiency, but believes it's a necessary step towards a future where AI serves humanity. 'We can't build superintelligence just for superintelligence's sake,' he said. 'It's got to be for humanity's sake, for a future we actually want to live in.'

title: Who is Zara Rahim, the Florida graduate and strategist behind Zohran Mamdanis historic New York City win?
description: Zohran Mamdani's historic mayoral win in New York City was a culmination of a decade-long journey for Zara Rahim, his senior adviser. Rahim, a University of Central Florida graduate, began her career in politics with the Obama campaign in 2012. She then worked at the White House, Uber, and Vogue magazine, honing her skills in digital politics and cultural storytelling. Rahim's approach emphasizes authenticity over optics, and she urged Mamdani's campaign to focus on the real New York. Her efforts paid off, with Mamdani's victory marked by deep, in-person engagement and digital virality. 'Politics is culture,' Rahim has said, reflecting her connection between the two fields. 'I'm not just a politician's aide, I'm a storyteller,' she added. Rahim's journey is a testament to the power of technology and the importance of authenticity in shaping public opinion.

title: YouTube creator bans controversy: Why Endermans case has raised global concerns over AI-based moderation
description: YouTube's automated decision-making system has come under fire after popular YouTuber Enderman's channel was terminated without warning. Enderman, who has over 380,000 subscribers, received a message stating that his channel wasn't following YouTube's Terms of Service and was removed to protect the community. He appealed the decision, but felt it was 'useless' as the entire process seemed automated. Others, including Old Money Documentaries and ScratchitGaming, reported similar issues with their channels being deleted for 'spam, scam, or deceptive practices'. YouTube's official response claimed that some channels were 'mistakenly removed' and would be restored after review. However, many creators remain skeptical, questioning the role of AI bots in moderation and whether creators' livelihoods are safe in their hands. 'The decision was made by AI only,' Enderman said, sparking a debate about the power of AI moderation systems.

title: 'Grateful': Shreyas Iyer shares first update since near-fatal injury in Australia
description: Indian ODI vice-captain Shreyas Iyer has broken his silence after a scary spleen injury in the third ODI against Australia on October 25. Iyer, 30, spent nearly a week in hospital, including a few days in the ICU, and has now shared a cheerful picture on social media. In his Instagram post, he thanked fans for their love and care, saying 'Sun been a great therapy. Grateful to be back.' Iyer's condition was critical after suffering a life-threatening injury, but swift intervention by the Indian team's medical staff and local doctors in Sydney proved crucial. He was discharged on November 1, but is expected to miss the upcoming ODI series against South Africa starting November 30. The BCCI has thanked the doctors involved in Iyer's treatment, with a BCCI official stating that talk of a cricketing comeback is 'premature' and that physical and mental well-being is of utmost importance right now.

title: 'Playing well, but ': Ganguly on Jurel's selection amid growing clamour for inclusion
description: Former India captain Sourav Ganguly has weighed in on Dhruv Jurel's red-hot form, suggesting it may be challenging for the young wicketkeeper-batter to break into India's settled Test line-up. Speaking at an event, Ganguly praised Jurel's purple patch but noted that spots are taken in the team. He suggested that Jurel's inclusion could depend on whether the selectors want to send someone at No. 3, such as Sai Sudharsan. Ganguly also tipped India as overwhelming favourites at home, highlighting the team's formidable spin attack and recent form. "How easy will it be to open up a slot for Dhruv Jurel at this stage, I wouldn't know," Ganguly said. "Because India's spin attack is very good. And this young team went to England three months ago and played exceptionally well."

title: NSA starts probe into GPS spoofing at IGI airport
description: The National Security Adviser's office has launched an investigation into GPS spoofing at Delhi's IGI Airport, which has been affecting flight landings for weeks. The spoofing has caused planes to receive false location and terrain warnings, forcing some flights to divert to alternate airports. To mitigate the issue, the Directorate General of Civil Aviation has expedited the installation of a category-1 instrument landing system (ILS) on runway 10/28, which will enable planes to land safely even with GPS spoofing. The ILS calibration is scheduled for Tuesday, and Delhi International Airport Ltd has warned passengers that some flight schedules may be impacted during this time. 'Some flight schedules may be impacted' on Tuesday due to 'mandatory flight calibration of ILS', said DIAL. 'Regulated' flights will take place during this period, and passengers are advised to 'coordinate with airlines to get updated flight information status'.

title: SSC JE and SI Delhi Police exam dates declared: Check important schedule here
description: The Staff Selection Commission (SSC) has released the examination schedule for the Junior Engineer (JE) and Sub-Inspector (SI) in Delhi Police and Central Armed Police Forces (CAPFs) examinations for 2025. The Junior Engineer (Civil, Mechanical, and Electrical) Examination, 2025 (Paper-I) will be conducted from December 3 to December 6, 2025, while the Sub-Inspectors in Delhi Police and CAPFs Examination, 2025 (Paper-I) will be held from December 9 to December 12, 2025. Candidates are advised to keep track of further updates, including the release of admit cards and detailed exam instructions, on the official SSC portal.

title: IBPS Clerk result expected to be released at ibps.in soon: Check details here
description: IBPS Clerk result 2025: The Institute of Banking Personnel Selection (IBPS) is expected to declare the IBPS Clerk result (Customer Service Associate) soon on ibps.in. The recruitment drive aims to fill 13,533 vacancies for the post. Candidates who appeared in the preliminary examination are awaiting updates, as the results will determine eligibility for the next phase, the Main examination. The preliminary examination served as the first screening stage in the multi-tier recruitment process. Only those who clear the prelims cutoff will progress to the Mains Examination. The result once declared will be available on the official website. 'The Customer Service Associate role serves as the foundation of India's banking operations, handling customer relations, transactions, and administrative functions in branches nationwide,' said an IBPS official. Candidates can follow the steps mentioned on the official website to download the result once it is released.

title: NPCIL recruitment 2025: Registration window for Deputy Manager posts open at npcilcareers.co.in, check direct link to apply here
description: The Nuclear Power Corporation of India Limited (NPCIL) has announced recruitment for 122 Deputy Manager positions. Eligible candidates can apply online between 7 November 2025 and 27 November 2025. The selection process includes a written or online test, interview, personal assessment, and medical examination. Selected candidates will receive pay according to the PSU executive pay scale, along with allowances and other benefits. 'Candidates must hold an engineering degree or an equivalent professional qualification in the relevant discipline,' said an NPCIL spokesperson. Interested candidates can register online by following the steps outlined on the NPCIL careers website. The recruitment drive aims to fill the vacant positions in various disciplines. The NPCIL recruitment 2025 details include a total of 122 vacancies, with registration starting on 7 November 2025 and ending on 27 November 2025.

title: As ICE arrests rise, Florida schools see measurable declines in student test performance, study finds
description: A study by the National Bureau of Economic Research found that heightened immigration enforcement during the Trump administration may be affecting U.S. citizen students living in Spanish-speaking households. Researchers David Figlio and Umut zek discovered that student performance declined after immigration enforcement intensified, with a 10-15 SAT point drop associated with each one-percentage-point increase in immigration arrests. The impact was most severe in high-poverty schools and among students who were already struggling academically. Figlio noted that simply living in a community facing increased scrutiny can affect a child's learning, regardless of their citizenship status. The study's findings have broader implications for schools and educators, highlighting the need to consider the impact of immigration enforcement on student learning and well-being.

title: Americas new work reality: Why more people are taking multiple jobs to stay afloat
description: The modern workforce is undergoing a significant shift with 47% of American workers identifying as polyworkers, juggling multiple roles and industries to stay afloat. According to Monster's 2025 report, 51% of polyworkers rely on additional income to meet basic living costs. The willingness to push further is staggering, with nearly 59% admitting they would take on multiple full-time roles if circumstances demanded it. The pressures behind the hustle are complex, with 68% needing additional income for daily necessities and 46% working to pay off debt. The polyworking boom comes with trade-offs, with 29% saying it enhances productivity and creativity, but 31% feeling it drains focus and 26% admitting it has taken a toll on mental health. The rise of polyworking signals a cultural transformation, marking a turning point for organizations to adapt to a workforce that values autonomy over attachment.

title: Canal near Kartavya Path green with algae, pavements broken
description: Neglect in Delhi's Central Vista: Broken Pavements, Stagnant Canal, and Unauthorised Parking Lot. The redeveloped Kartavya Path, a major component of the Central Vista project, is marred by neglect. Sections of pavements are broken, a canal has stagnant water, and an unauthorised parking lot has been set up. Ministry sources claim that 10 refurnished canals are being regularly cleaned by the Central Public Works Department (CPWD), but admit that some aerators are not functioning. The area, under the jurisdiction of the housing and urban affairs ministry, is a stark contrast to the newly developed Kartavya Path. "This is another example of how maintenance gets less attention than new construction and development projects," said an official working at Krishi Bhawan. The neglect is evident in the green areas and landscape near Krishi Bhawan, which have been neglected for months and are only spruced up ahead of Republic Day.

title: Jawaharlal Nehru Stadium may be demolished, remade as sports city
description: Delhi's iconic Jawaharlal Nehru (JLN) Stadium, built for the 1982 Asian Games, is set to undergo a major makeover. The sports ministry plans to redevelop the 102-acre complex into a state-of-the-art sports city, inspired by Qatar's Sports City. The project will include a lodging facility for athletes and world-class infrastructure for training and hosting major events. The estimated cost and timeline have not been worked out, but officials say the planning is in the proposal stage. The JLN stadium will be dismantled and redeveloped, with all offices, including the Sports Authority of India and National Anti-Doping Agency, to be relocated. The project aims to utilize the land to its optimal level, currently only 28% is being used. The stadium has hosted several prestigious international events, including the Delhi CWG 2010 and U17 FIFA World Cup in 2017.

title: IAF AFCAT-I 2026 registration begins at afcat.edcil.co.in: Apply by December 9, direct link here
description: The Indian Air Force (IAF) has opened the registration window for AFCAT 01/2026, inviting men and women graduates to join as Group A Gazetted Officers. The online registration began on 10 November 2025 and will continue until 9 December 2025. The Air Force Common Admission Test (AFCAT) is a primary gateway for recruiting young officers into the IAF. Selected candidates will undergo a rigorous selection process, including a written exam, AFSB interview, and medical evaluation. Eligibility criteria include being an Indian citizen, meeting age and educational qualifications, and meeting medical and physical fitness standards. Interested candidates can register online at afcat.cdac.in or afcat.edcil.co.in. The AFCAT-I exam is scheduled for January 2026, giving candidates ample time to prepare. "This recruitment drive invites both men and women graduates to take part in a rigorous selection process," said an IAF spokesperson. "With AFCAT-I exam scheduled to be held in January 2026, candidates have ample time to prepare."

title: Trumps Kiss Moment With Erika Kirk Sparks Outrage; Predator-In-Chief Trends
description: Former Duke of York Andrew Mountbatten Windsor is reportedly seeking refuge in a $20 million Abu Dhabi villa within a royal compound owned by UAE President Sheikh Mohamed bin Zayed Al Nahyan. The move comes amid the ongoing Jeffrey Epstein firestorm and a new U.S. Congressional summons. According to sources, Andrew has made it '100 per cent clear' that he won't face another public grilling in America, believing he's been 'hounded and humiliated' beyond repair. This development follows King Charles' decision to strip Andrew of his royal titles, citing renewed scrutiny over Epstein-linked documents released by Congress. Andrew's 'escape' plan has sparked controversy, with many questioning the motives behind his decision to flee the country.

title: Nithari serial killings case: SC acquits Surendra Koli; orders immediate release
description: The Supreme Court has allowed a curative petition filed by Surendra Koli, challenging his conviction and death sentence in one of the Nithari murder cases. Koli will now walk free, as he has already been acquitted in all other Nithari cases. The Nithari killings came to light in 2006, with skeletal remains of eight children discovered in a drain behind a businessman's house in Noida's Nithari village. Koli was convicted for the rape and murder of a 15-year-old girl, with his conviction upheld by the Supreme Court in 2011. However, in 2015, the Allahabad high court commuted his death sentence to life imprisonment, citing an inordinate delay in deciding his mercy petition. The acquittal of Koli and co-accused Moninder Singh Pandher in multiple Nithari cases was upheld by the Supreme Court in July this year, dismissing all 14 appeals. "With this decision, Koli will now walk free," said a Supreme Court bench, comprising Chief Justice BR Gavai and Justices Surya Kant and Vikram Nath.

title: No rabies deaths in city from '22 to '24, said government in parliament; RTI finds 18
description: Contrary to the Union government's claim, 18 people in Delhi died from rabies between 2022 and 2024, according to RTI data. The data reveals six deaths in 2022, two in 2023, and 10 in 2024 at MVID Hospital. This contradicts the minister's written reply in the Lok Sabha, which stated 'zero human rabies deaths' in Delhi from January 2022 to January 2025. The data mismatch raises questions over coordination between health surveillance systems and the accuracy of reporting mechanisms for rabies. 'Rabies is 100% preventable yet almost always fatal once symptoms appear,' said a health expert. The National Rabies Control Programme aims to eliminate dog-mediated rabies by 2030 through mass dog vaccination, sterilisation, and anti-rabies vaccine availability.

title: IBPS RRB PET 2025 link activated: Check details here
description: The Institute of Banking Personnel Selection (IBPS) has activated the Pre-Examination Training (PET) link for the Regional Rural Banks (RRB) examination 2025. Eligible candidates can access the link on ibps.in between November 10 and November 15, 2025. The PET facility is designed to help aspirants, particularly those from reserved categories, acquire familiarity with the examination process. Candidates can register and attend the PET sessions online through their IBPS login credentials. The preliminary examination call letters will be issued in November or December 2025, with online examinations scheduled for November 22-23 and December 6-14, 2025. "Candidates can follow the steps mentioned here to check the IBPS RRB PET link," said the institute. "Visit the official IBPS website, click on the 'IBPS RRB Exam 2025 PET' link, enter login credentials, submit, and complete the training module."

title: National Education Day 2025: Why India observes it on November 11
description: India observes National Education Day on November 11 to commemorate Maulana Abul Kalam Azad, the country's first Education Minister. Azad's vision for education emphasized access and equality, with a focus on free and compulsory primary education, adult literacy programs, and girls' education. He believed education builds confidence, awareness, and shared purpose. Many institutions that define Indian education today, such as the University Grants Commission and Indian Institutes of Technology, were born during his tenure. On National Education Day, schools and colleges reflect on why education still matters, with students participating in essay writing, debates, and quizzes. Azad's legacy continues to inspire, with his message that education is not only a path to progress but also a force that can shape an entire society.

title: After $400 million in grants were canceled, Columbia taps endowment reserves to support its research programs
description: Columbia University has utilized its unrestricted endowment funds to maintain its research programs after federal support disruptions. According to Anne Sullivan, executive vice president for finance, the university began using these funds in fiscal year 2025 and will continue to do so in 2026. This decision marks a rare financial step for the Ivy League institution, which typically follows a formulaic approach to endowment spending. Columbia's move reflects a broader trend among major universities balancing financial prudence with operational needs. "Institutions are trying to mitigate risk wherever they can," said Chuck Ambrose, a senior education consultant at Husch Blackwell. "They're using asset management to underwrite operating challenges while maintaining long-term discipline."

title: Vladimir Putin Looks Frail? Sore Hand Footage Triggers Health Alarm Across The Globe
description: Former Duke of York Andrew Windsor is reportedly seeking refuge in a $20 million Abu Dhabi villa within a royal compound owned by UAE President Sheikh Mohamed bin Zayed Al Nahyan. The move comes amid the ongoing Jeffrey Epstein firestorm and a new U.S. Congressional summons. According to sources, Andrew has made it '100 per cent clear' that he won't face another public grilling in America, believing he's been 'hounded and humiliated' beyond repair. This development follows King Charles' decision to strip Andrew of his royal titles, citing renewed scrutiny over Epstein-linked documents released by Congress. The relocation plan is said to be an 'escape' plan for Andrew, who is facing intense media scrutiny and public backlash.

title: Crowd gaaliyan de raha tha': Azam Khan heartbreaking tale of abuses and tears
description: Pakistan batter Azam Khan has opened up about the lowest phase of his international career, recalling struggles during his stint with the national team. He failed to register a single half-century in 14 T20Is between 2021 and 2024, drawing criticism for his fitness and fielding. Azam's time with the national side was marked by inconsistent performances and questions over his wicketkeeping. In a recent video interview, he revisited a tough experience facing England's Mark Wood, who bowled two bouncers in a row. Azam recalled a painful moment at The Oval, where he faced brutal criticism from the crowd and was dismissed for zero in a heavy defeat for Pakistan. He questioned, 'Is this my reputation?' and broke down in tears, feeling his career was going downhill. Azam's last appearance came during the 2024 T20 World Cup, where Pakistan crashed out before the semi-finals.

title: YouTuber Candace Owens sparks TPUSA feud after hinting Charlie Kirks own mentors plotted his death claims Alex Clark
description: Turning Point USA host Alex Clark has accused Candace Owens of almost blaming Charlie Kirk's close friends and mentors for his death. Clark posted on X that Candace's words made it sound like people close to Charlie were behind his death, and she 'stopped just short of outright accusing them of orchestrating his death.' Owens had previously questioned Tyler Robinson's role in Charlie's death, claiming she didn't believe he was the killer. However, Clark pointed out that Owens had 'leaks' as her source and admitted she hadn't read the part about the messages not existing. Clark also criticized Owens for double standards, saying she felt 'icky' about the timing and tone of his Wall Street Journal interview but not her own CNN interview. The fight between Clark and Owens has divided people within Turning Point USA and among their fans online.

title: Americas paycheck pause: Why workers are choosing job security over raises
description: Millions of American workers are struggling with stagnant pay, with 41% not receiving a meaningful raise in over two years. A recent report by Zety found that 61% of employees are willing to accept smaller or no raises for job stability. The report reveals a cultural shift where raises are no longer seen as automatic markers of growth but as indicators of an organization's financial health. Employees are trading ambition for assurance, with 50% saying they're just glad to have a job and 36% feeling underpaid but stuck. Companies are tightening their belts, with 89% reducing budgets for raises and bonuses. The evolving workplace mood reveals a redefinition of career success, with workers prioritizing non-monetary rewards such as health insurance, paid time off, and remote work options.

title: Government eases rules to boost cornea donation ecosystem
description: The Union health ministry has notified the Transplantation of Human Organs and Tissues (Amendment) Rules, 2025, to streamline corneal transplantation centres and improve accessibility to eye donation and transplantation services. The amendment, issued on November 6, scraps the mandatory requirement of Clinical Specular equipment at corneal transplantation centres, easing infrastructural and operational challenges for smaller eye centres in rural and semi-urban areas. According to officials, the amendment will strengthen the country's cornea donation and transplantation ecosystem. 'This change has been introduced after careful consideration of expert recommendations and stakeholder consultations,' said officials. The amendment is expected to enhance the overall availability and accessibility to corneal transplantation services across the country.

title: Warren Buffett educational qualifications: From Harvard rejection to becoming the 'Oracle of Omaha'
description: Warren Buffett, the 'Oracle of Omaha,' has an estimated net worth of $150 billion as of November 2025. His journey from a curious child in Omaha to the helm of Berkshire Hathaway was shaped by education and instinct. Buffett's early exposure to business came through small ventures and visits to his father's brokerage office. He attended the University of Nebraska, graduating at 20, and later earned a Master of Science in Economics from Columbia. He applied the principles he learned from Benjamin Graham to found Buffett Partnership Ltd. in 1956 and acquired control of Berkshire Hathaway in 1965. Buffett's disciplined approach to value investing, long-term vision, and frugality have made him a global investment powerhouse. His story underscores the value of education, curiosity, and perseverance, and serves as a reminder that learning is both a path and a tool that shapes careers and legacies.

title: Princess Kate Middletons Ice-Queen Persona Becomes Her Strongest Weapon | WATCH
description: Former Duke of York Andrew Windsor is reportedly seeking refuge in a $20 million Abu Dhabi villa, owned by UAE President Sheikh Mohamed bin Zayed Al Nahyan. According to RadarOnline, Andrew has been offered the villa as an 'escape' from the ongoing Jeffrey Epstein firestorm and a new U.S. Congressional summons. Sources claim Andrew has made it '100 per cent clear' he won't face another public grilling in America, believing he's been 'hounded and humiliated' beyond repair. This development comes after King Charles stripped Andrew of his royal titles following renewed scrutiny over Epstein-linked documents released by Congress.

title: NCW recommends legal definition, penalties under criminal law to counter deep fake abuse
description: The National Commission for Women has recommended the inclusion of a clear legal definition and strict penalties under the Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita (BNS) 2023 to address deep fake abuse. The commission has proposed a new section to define 'modified content' as digitally created or altered images, videos, or audio that falsely depict any person in an explicit, defamatory, or misleading manner. The report calls for a comprehensive review of cyber laws relating to women to secure their digital rights and hold online platforms accountable. The commission has also recommended inclusion of cyberbullying, trolling, and privacy violations in the BNS 2023. According to the report, any person who creates, distributes, or possesses deep fake content targeting women without their consent shall be punishable with imprisonment for up to three years or a fine. The commission has made over 200 recommendations to address the legal and institutional gaps in India's response to cyber offences.

title: Media MELTDOWN: Trumps $1.5B Threat Sends BBC Into Crisis After Fake Documentary Fallout | WATCH
description: Former Duke of York Andrew Mountbatten Windsor is reportedly planning to relocate to Abu Dhabi, escaping the ongoing Jeffrey Epstein firestorm and a new U.S. Congressional summons. According to RadarOnline, Andrew has been offered refuge in a $20 million villa within a royal compound owned by UAE President Sheikh Mohamed bin Zayed Al Nahyan, a longtime acquaintance. Sources claim Andrew has made it '100 per cent clear' he won't face another public grilling in America, believing he's been 'hounded and humiliated' beyond repair. This development comes days after King Charles stripped Andrew of his royal titles following renewed scrutiny over Epstein-linked documents.

title: WB Constable written exam admit card 2025 released at wbpolice.gov.in: Direct link to download hall tickets
description: The West Bengal Police Recruitment Board (WBPRB) has released the admit cards for the West Bengal Police Constable Written Examination 2025. The exam will be held on November 30, 2025, and aims to fill 11,749 vacancies. Candidates can download their admit cards from the official website, wbpolice.gov.in, by following the steps mentioned. It is crucial to verify the details on the admit card, including name, roll number, photograph, and examination centre, and report any discrepancies to the authorities. Only hard copies of the admit card will be accepted, and candidates must carry it to the examination centre. 'The admit card is a mandatory document for entry into the examination hall,' authorities have stated. Candidates are advised to stay tuned to the official website for complete details on the recruitment process.

title: Women largest minority, says Supreme Court; to hear plea for immediate quota
description: The Supreme Court has agreed to hear a plea seeking immediate implementation of 33% reservation for women in Lok Sabha and state assemblies. The court expressed reluctance but decided to examine the petition after senior advocate Shobha Gupta argued that the constitutional amendment cannot be put on hold indefinitely. Justice B V Nagarathna hailed the amendment, stating that women are the largest minority in the country and it would bring them justice. The court will seek clarity from the government on the census and delimitation process, which is required for implementation. The petition argues that several constitutional amendments on reservations were implemented immediately without being tied to the completion of any census or delimitation exercise. 'The constitutional amendment cannot be put on hold for an uncertain period,' Gupta said. 'There is no reason to wait for the delimitation process and the reservation can be done for women by rotating the reserved seats.'

title: Michigan schools face tough choice as $321 million safety plan includes legal waiver condition
description: Michigan school districts are facing a difficult decision: accept millions in state funding for school safety and mental health programs or protect their legal rights. The 2025-26 state budget includes $321 million for these services, but districts that apply must waive attorney-client privilege and cooperate with state investigations in the event of a mass-casualty event. This requirement follows concerns after the Oxford High School shooting in 2021, where the district's internal investigation was hindered by employee non-participation. Several education associations have urged state leaders to reconsider the language, citing 'significant legal and operational challenges.' Districts have until November 30 to apply, and it remains unclear whether lawmakers will act before the deadline.

title: HTET answer key 2025 released at bseh.org.in: Direct link to download here
description: The Board of School Education, Haryana (BSEH) has released the HTET 2024 answer key for all levels, PRT, TGT, and PGT. Candidates can access the provisional answer keys on the board's official website, bseh.org.in. The answer keys allow candidates to cross-check their responses and calculate their probable scores ahead of the final results. The HTET 2024 examination was conducted on July 30 and 31 across Haryana. "The answer keys provide a crucial opportunity for candidates to evaluate their performance," said a BSEH spokesperson. "We advise candidates to keep checking the official website for the latest updates regarding the objection schedule, final answer key, and certificate verification procedures." Candidates can download the answer key by visiting the official website, selecting the relevant post, and clicking on the "HTET 2024 Answer Key" link.

title: US has sent $7.5m to Equatorial Guinea to accept noncitizens deportees
description: The US has sent $7.5m to Equatorial Guinea, a repressive regime, to accept noncitizen deportees. This is the first time the Migration and Refugee Assistance fund has been used for deportation instead of refugee resettlement. The move has raised concerns over human trafficking and human rights abuses. According to Jeanne Shaheen, the top-ranking Democratic senator on the Senate foreign relations committee, the payment is 'highly unusual' given the country's history of corruption and government officials' complicity in human trafficking. The deal fits the administration's contentious third-country deportation push, which has alarmed human rights monitors. The US has approached at least 58 governments about accepting deportees, often securing agreements through cash payments or diplomatic pressure. 'Implementing the Trump Administration's immigration policies is a top priority for the Department of State,' said a state department spokesperson. The US has also met with Equatorial Guinea's vice-president, who was convicted of embezzlement and money laundering in 2017.

title: Nauruan president makes surprise visit to meet Albanese government as another man quietly deported to Pacific island
description: Nauruan President David Adeang met with Australian officials in Canberra on Remembrance Day, amidst controversy over alleged links between his government and an Australian bikie gang. Adeang met with Home Affairs Minister Tony Burke and Foreign Affairs Minister Penny Wong, discussing 'recent media reports'. The meeting comes as Nauru receives its fourth member from the NZYQ cohort, a group of 350 people affected by a $2.5bn deal. Critics have raised concerns over transparency and corruption, with some NZYQ members serving jail terms for violent crimes. Greens Senator David Shoebridge has referred the matter to the National Anti-Corruption Commission. Burke described the meeting as 'productive', while Shadow Home Affairs Minister Jonathon Duniam questioned the lack of prior notice and diplomatic protocol.

title: Japan and China in growing row after PM Takaichi says Taiwan conflict could trigger military deployment
description: Japan and China are locked in a heated dispute over Tokyo's potential military involvement in a conflict over Taiwan. Japan's Prime Minister Sanae Takaichi said an attack on Taiwan could trigger the deployment of Japan's self-defence forces if the conflict posed an existential threat to Japan. China's consul general in Osaka, Xue Jian, responded with a threatening post on X, calling for Japan to be 'cut off' for its 'dirty neck' comments. Tokyo condemned the post as 'extremely inappropriate' and urged its removal. The row comes after Takaichi met with Chinese leader Xi Jinping at the Apec summit, where they vowed to build 'constructive and stable' relations. Japan has long wrestled with how to respond to a conflict between China and Taiwan, which lies just 100km from its westernmost island. 'We strongly protested and urged that it be taken down immediately,' Japan's senior government spokesperson Minoru Kihara said. 'China strongly urges Japan to reflect on its historical culpability on the Taiwan issue... and stop sending any wrong signals to Taiwan independence separatist forces,' a Chinese foreign ministry spokesperson said.

title: Chinas CO2 emissions have been flat or falling for past 18 months, analysis finds
description: China's carbon dioxide emissions have been flat or falling for 18 months, exceeding hopes that the world's biggest polluter has hit its peak CO2 emissions target ahead of schedule. The Centre for Research on Energy and Clean Air analysis found CO2 emissions remained unchanged from a year earlier in the third quarter, thanks to declining emissions in the travel, cement, and steel industries. Rapid growth in solar and wind power generation, which increased by 46% and 11% respectively, contributed to this trend. China's president, Xi Jinping, did not attend the UN climate conference, but the Chinese delegation is present for the talks. Andr Corra do Lago, the Brazilian diplomat and president of Cop30, praised Chinese progress on green technologies, saying 'China is coming up with solutions that are for everyone, not just China.' However, experts warn that China's dual carbon goals are still ambitious, and the country needs to make steeper reductions to hit its 2030 goal of reducing carbon intensity by 65%. The 15th five-year plan, which outlines the government's priority and policies for 2026-2030, will be crucial in determining China's path towards a low-carbon future.

title: Linda Reynolds bankruptcy proceedings against Brittany Higgins stalled by paperwork glitch
description: Former Senator Linda Reynolds' bid to recover $2.4m compensation payout from Brittany Higgins has been delayed due to a bankruptcy paperwork glitch. Higgins was ordered to pay 80% of Reynolds' $1m+ legal costs after a defamation win. Reynolds' lawyer, Martin Bennett, expressed disappointment that Higgins has not paid a cent towards the judgment. If Higgins is declared bankrupt, a trustee could investigate a trust she allegedly used to protect her commonwealth payout. Higgins apologized to Reynolds after losing the defamation trial, which found she made 26 false or misleading statements about Reynolds. Higgins' husband, David Sharaz, is also expected to declare bankruptcy after being served with a notice by Reynolds.

title: Paul Keating says he advised Gough Whitlam to put John Kerr under police arrest during dismissal saga
description: Former Australian Prime Minister Paul Keating has revealed he advised his predecessor Gough Whitlam to arrest the Governor General Sir John Kerr during the 1975 dismissal crisis. Keating described the incident as a 'coup' that 'never really recovered' Australian politics. In a recent interview with journalist Niki Savva, Keating said he suggested Whitlam ask the Queen to appoint a new Governor General, and if Kerr resisted, he should be put under police arrest. However, Whitlam was not supportive of the idea, citing concerns about a potential standoff between military and police. Keating's analysis aligns with the current Prime Minister Anthony Albanese's description of the dismissal as a 'calculated plot' to remove a democratically elected government. Keating recalled attending a meeting between Kerr and Whitlam just five days before the dismissal, where they engaged in 'boisterous banter' with no hint of the impending crisis. Keating described Kerr's dismissal of Whitlam as 'in every respect, a coup'.

title: Planes came within metres of hitting Melbourne airport workers in terrifying incidents after runway shortened
description: Two passenger planes narrowly avoided colliding with construction vehicles and workers during takeoff at Melbourne airport in 2023 due to flight crews being unaware of a shortened runway. The Australian Transport Safety Bureau (ATSB) released a final report into the incidents, which occurred 11 days apart. The runway had been temporarily shortened from 3,657 metres to 2,089 metres for night-time resurfacing works. In the first incident, a Malaysia Airlines Airbus A330-300 overran the runway, passing less than seven metres above workers and construction vehicles. The Bamboo Airways Boeing 787-9 also narrowly missed workers by 4.5 metres. No physical injuries were recorded. The ATSB's investigation found that flight crews had not absorbed critical information about the runway changes due to expectations, workload, and time pressures. ATSB chief commissioner Angus Mitchell said, These were serious incidents... it was by luck that we didnt have an impact. The incidents have prompted changes to domestic and international practices on notifying flight crews about critical safety information.

title: Alan Jones sexual abuse case to hear from 139 witnesses over up to four months
description: Radio host Alan Jones, 84, faces 25 charges of indecent assault and 2 of sexual touching against 9 alleged victims. The hearing, scheduled to start on August 3, 2026, could run until December. Jones's defence team claims he was kept in the dark about the police investigation and is seeking a reconsideration of the decision to hold the hearing in the local court. Prosecutors argue that Jones's team is stalling, and the defence solicitor Bryan Wrench says there is an 'iceberg of exculpatory material'. Jones denies the charges, which follow an eight-month police investigation. He was arrested in November 2024 and has pleaded not guilty to all charges.

title: Nexperia row shows how China is weaponising trade  and winning
description: The Dutch government's takeover of Nexperia, a Chinese-owned chip factory, has escalated tensions between Europe and China. Beijing has agreed to ease restrictions on automotive chip supplies to the EU, but only for a 12-month period and for civilian use. This has raised concerns about China's asymmetric relationship with Europe and its potential to interfere in the EU's defence industry. Andrew Small, a senior fellow at the German Marshall Fund, said, 'We can buy a bit of time, but there is a sense that we are entering into a situation where we are going to be dealing with rolling crises from now on.' China's trade deficit with the EU stands at 300bn, and the bloc's tariff measures have done little to stem the tide of imports. Jens Eskelund, chair of the European Chamber of Commerce in China, warned that Europe's dependency on China in strategic industries such as clean tech could lead to a decline in production. 'We are living in a period of change unseen in 100 years,' he said. China's actions have raised concerns about its use of trading relationships as a means of projecting power and extracting economic advantage.

title: Hopes of Irish language revival in public life as Catherine Connolly takes office
description: Catherine Connolly, Ireland's incoming president, is set to make Gaelic a central part of her presidency, aiming to bring the language from the margins and use it as the working language. Connolly, a fluent Irish speaker, won a landslide election, uniting opposition leftwing parties and energizing young voters. Her presidency comes amid a growing revival of the Irish language, with efforts to promote its use in schools, media, and public life. "I will do my best to bring Irish in from the margins and use it," Connolly said. "She has brought the language to the centre of national debate," said Conchr  Muadaigh, a spokesperson for Conradh na Gaeilge. "She doesnt treat it as a cultural afterthought or decoration.
