Its something she genuinely believes in."

title: Second man deported under one in, one out scheme returns to UK on small boat
description: A second person removed to France under the UK-France 'one in, one out' deal has returned to the UK, the Home Office confirmed. The individual, whose age and nationality are undisclosed, was detected by biometrics and detained immediately. This is the second person to return to the UK after being removed to France, following an Iranian man on October 18. A Home Office spokesperson stated, "Anyone looking to return to the UK after being removed under the UK-France agreement is wasting their time and money." Shadow Home Secretary Chris Philp criticized the government's handling of migrant chaos, saying the deal has "clearly lost control of our borders." The Home Office has not confirmed the total number of people who arrived on Sunday, but it's estimated to be nearly 400. The 'one in, one out' scheme aims to deter people smugglers, but critics argue it has had little effect, with around 20,000 arrivals since the deal's announcement.

title: Turkish authorities arrest eight people and suspend 1,024 players in betting investigation
description: Turkish authorities have arrested eight people, including Eyupspor chairman Murat zkaya, in a betting scandal investigation. The Turkish Football Federation (TFF) has suspended 1,024 players and 149 referees pending disciplinary investigations. The TFF president, Ibrahim Haciosmanoglu, described the situation as a 'moral crisis in Turkish football'. The federation has requested a 15-day transfer window from Fifa to allow clubs to complete their squads. 'Due to the precautionary transfer of 1,024 football players to the PFDK, negotiations have been initiated urgently with Fifa to grant a 15-day transfer and registration period,' the TFF said. The investigation found that 371 of 571 active referees in Turkey's professional leagues had betting accounts, with some referees placing bets over 1,000 times. The TFF has suspended matches in the second- and third-tier leagues for two weeks, and its board will hold an extraordinary meeting on Tuesday.

title: Olympians call on Iran to halt execution of boxing champion
description: More than 20 Olympic medallists, coaches, and athletes have signed a letter calling for the halt of the execution of Iranian boxing champion Mohammad Javad Vafaei Sani, who is on death row for participating in nationwide protests in 2019. The letter, signed by Martina Navratilova and Sharron Davies, among others, condemns Iran's use of capital punishment as a tool of oppression. Vafaei Sani has spent five years in prison, where he has been tortured and kept in solitary confinement. The signatories call on the United Nations, international sports federations, and governments to act immediately to save his life. Iran has a history of executing athletes for their beliefs, including Habib Khabiri and Fourouzan Abdi. The execution crisis in Iran has reached horrific proportions, with at least 853 people executed in 2023, a 48% increase from 2022. The Iranian authorities have used the death penalty to suppress dissent and instil fear among the population.

title: Advisers told ministers banning Palestine Action could make it more popular
description: A government document reveals that ministers were warned that banning Palestine Action could 'inadvertently enhance' the group's profile. The briefing paper, prepared in March, cautioned that a ban could be a divisive issue and heighten Muslim-Jewish tensions. Despite this, the group was proscribed under terrorism laws in June. Huda Ammori, a co-founder of Palestine Action, said the ban has backfired, increasing awareness and popularity of the group. The document warned that some may see the decision as an attack on civil liberties, with a creep of terrorism powers into the realm of free expression and protest. A Home Office spokesperson stated that Palestine Action's activities put the public's safety and security at risk, but a counter-terrorism policing spokesperson said decisions on proscription are for the government to make.

title: Crime gangs in UK start making own branded weight-loss drugs
description: Organised crime gangs are manufacturing their own branded weight-loss drugs, designed to look like legitimate medicines. The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) has conducted the largest single seizure of trafficked weight-loss drugs, warning of a significant threat. According to Andy Morling, head of the MHRA's criminal enforcement unit, the new model of production involves investment in designing packaging and branding, making the products look like genuine medicines. Morling stated, 'That is an unusual model. [What they seized] looked like genuine medicines, but are entirely unlicensed and illegal to sell in the UK.' The MHRA has seized tens of thousands of empty weight-loss pens and over 2,000 unlicensed pens in a raid on an illegal factory in Northampton. Morling emphasized the importance of public safety, saying, 'We take a proportionate approach to the threat posed ... The priority in every case is public safety by removing products from the market.'

title: Tuesday briefing: What the BBCs new crisis reveals about its failures  and future
description: BBC Crisis: Governance Failures and Political Agenda Exposed The sudden resignations of BBC director general Tim Davie and head of BBC News Deborah Turness have sparked a crisis at the UK's public service broadcaster. The departures follow a week of attacks orchestrated by the right-wing press and figures associated with the Conservative party. The Guardian's media editor, Michael Savage, attributes the crisis to editorial issues, governance failures, and a political agenda against the BBC. He notes that the BBC has failed to defend itself, allowing the situation to escalate. The charter renewal is imminent in 2027, raising questions about the BBC's future. This crisis is reminiscent of previous BBC crises, including the 2004 resignation of director general Greg Dyke and the 2012 resignation of George Entwistle. The BBC must address its governance failures and defend its editorial independence to ensure its continued relevance and integrity.

title: Success is shutting them down: Met police in fight against illegal vape and phone shops
description: A nationwide crackdown on high street crime, known as Operation Machinize 2, has led to the raid of six electrical goods outlets in south London. The Metropolitan police, HM Revenue and Customs, the local authority, and Trading Standards have seized over 10.7m in suspected illegal proceeds, 111,000 illegal vapes, 70kg of cannabis, and 4.5m illegal cigarettes. Inspector Oliver Lamb, overseeing the operation, stated, 'It's not the first time we have been to some of these shops  for some it's been the third visit this year.' The raids are part of a nationwide effort to combat the 'grey economy' and money laundering. Police have found that many of the products, including Apple-branded items, are counterfeit. The operation has resulted in 924 arrests and over 2,700 premises being targeted. Local residents have mixed reactions to the raids, with some expressing frustration and others appearing unperturbed.

title: Trump scolds air traffic controllers and blames rivals for economy in interview
description: In an exclusive interview on Fox News, President Donald Trump criticized air traffic controllers, blamed Democrats for economic indicators, and claimed that increased access to food stamps has put the country 'in jeopardy'. Trump also discussed his vision for addressing healthcare subsidies, suggesting 'Trump Care' where individuals buy their own health insurance. He stood by his claim of sending a $10,000 bonus to air traffic controllers who worked throughout the shutdown, despite uncertainty over funding. Trump denied affordability concerns, calling it a 'con job' by Democrats, and blamed Joe Biden and Jerome Powell for the economy's performance. He reiterated that the US economy is the strongest it has ever been, despite criticism from rivals and allies. Trump also championed Republican policies and credited GOP legislators for the outcome of the shutdown.

title: Trump asks supreme court to throw out jurys finding in E Jean Carroll lawsuit
description: Donald Trump has asked the US supreme court to throw out a $5m verdict in a civil lawsuit brought by writer E Jean Carroll, who accused him of sexually abusing her at a Manhattan department store in the 1990s. Trump's lawyers argue that the jury's finding was 'propped up' by 'indefensible evidentiary rulings' and that Carroll's claims are a 'politically motivated hoax'. Carroll testified that Trump turned a friendly encounter into a violent attack in 1996. Trump's lawyers claim that there is no physical or DNA evidence to corroborate Carroll's story. A three-judge appellate panel upheld the verdict in December 2024, and Trump's lawyers are now seeking review by the supreme court, whose conservative majority could be more open to considering his challenge. Trump's lawyers say the appeal is part of his crusade against 'Liberal Lawfare' and that the American people stand with him against 'Witch Hunts'.

title: Senate approves funding deal to end longest US government shutdown
description: The US Senate has approved a funding package to end the longest government shutdown in history, with a 60-40 vote. The deal, which funds most federal agencies through January, does not directly address expiring tax credits for healthcare premiums. Seven Democrats and one independent joined Republicans to pass the compromise, despite fierce backlash from their party. Senate Majority Leader John Thune has promised a Senate vote later this year on the subsidies. President Donald Trump has expressed support for the deal, saying it's 'very good.' Democrats have been fighting for the permanent extension of subsidies, which are scheduled to expire at the end of the year. 'This was the only deal on the table,' said Senator Jeanne Shaheen, defending her decision to vote for the bill. The deal also includes language to stop mass federal firings and reverse dismissals, and guarantees back pay to workers who have spent weeks without paychecks.

title: Two dead after small plane on hurricane relief trip to Jamaica crashes in Florida
description: A small turboprop plane on a hurricane relief mission to Jamaica crashed into a pond in Coral Springs, killing two people shortly after takeoff. The plane, a Beechcraft King Air, took off from the Fort Lauderdale executive airport at 10:14am and crashed at 10:19am. Emergency crews responded quickly, but no victims were initially found. Divers later searched the pond and found no bodies. The plane's debris scattered across a resident's yard, contaminating their pool and back porch with spilled fuel. The cause of the crash is under investigation by federal aviation officials. The plane was registered to International Air Services, a company specializing in trust agreements for non-US citizens. The crash occurred in a neighborhood with a significant Caribbean American community, which had been collecting relief supplies for Jamaica after Hurricane Melissa. The storm made landfall in Jamaica on October 28, causing widespread destruction and prompting relief efforts.

title: Godofredo Pepey Castros cause of death: 38-year-old ex-UFC fighter found dead in prison
description: Former UFC featherweight fighter Godofredo 'Pepey' Castro, 38, was found dead in a Florida jail cell. Authorities say no foul play is suspected, and the cause of death is pending. Castro had been in custody since June, facing multiple domestic violence charges. His passing has sparked conversations about mental health support for professional fighters. Castro's former teammate Rony Mariano Bezerra expressed his grief, saying 'he couldn't handle the pressure' and 'ended up taking his own life.' Castro competed 11 times in the UFC, earning three performance bonuses, and had a 13-7 professional record. He was arrested in June for allegedly assaulting his wife, with the case pending at the time of his death.
